<div class="gm-nav"><div class="gm-wrap"><a class="gm-brand" href="#top"><img src="{{ $logoUrl }}" alt="GLF MaT logo"><div><span>Restaurant & kitchen</span><strong>GLF MaT</strong></div></a><div class="gm-links"><a href="#menu-wall">Menu</a><a href="#promos">Promos</a><a href="#roster">Kitchens</a><a href="#experience">Experience</a></div></div></div>
<section class="gm-hero" id="top"><div class="gm-wrap"><div class="gm-heroGrid"><div class="gm-reveal is-visible"><div class="gm-kicker">Ukrainian x Azerbaijani cuisine / restaurant poster landing</div><h1 class="gm-title">GLF MaT<span>kitchen theatre.</span></h1><p class="gm-copy">This design takes inspiration from the quality level of the reels, but not their layouts directly. Instead of embedding videos, the page now behaves like a crafted restaurant campaign: bold poster hierarchy, menu-wall structure, promo blocks, dramatic whitespace, warm material color and a more memorable kitchen identity.</p><div class="gm-actions"><a class="gm-btn" href="#menu-wall">Open the menu wall</a><a class="gm-btnGhost" href="#promos">See promo blocks</a></div><div class="gm-strip"><div class="gm-stat"><strong>12</strong><span>menu stars</span></div><div class="gm-stat"><strong>3</strong><span>cuisine scenes</span></div><div class="gm-stat"><strong>6</strong><span>promo blocks</span></div><div class="gm-stat"><strong>{{ $restaurants->count() }}</strong><span>live kitchens</span></div></div></div><div class="gm-stage gm-reveal is-visible"><div class="gm-stageGrid"><article class="gm-logoPoster"><img src="{{ $logoUrl }}" alt="GLF MaT crest"><h2>Chef hat. Flame. Mountain line. Grill.</h2><p>The brand sign becomes the anchor, while the rest of the page acts like a premium menu campaign instead of a default service category.</p></article><div class="gm-board"><article class="gm-boardCard"><small>Visual thesis</small><h3>Poster-like hero, sculpted blocks, warm paper finish.</h3><p>Large shapes, intentional spacing, and fewer but stronger elements give the page the same confidence the best reels had.</p></article><article class="gm-boardCard"><small>Kitchen thesis</small><h3>Ukraine brings comfort. Azerbaijan brings flame.</h3><p>The page stages those two energies against each other, then resolves them in one menu and one room.</p></article><article class="gm-boardCard"><small>Interaction thesis</small><h3>Scroll reveals, menu tabs, animated promo wall.</h3><p>Motion stays restrained but visible so the design feels alive without depending on embedded reference videos.</p></article></div></div></div></div><div class="gm-marquee"><div class="gm-marqueeTrack"><span>borscht reserve</span><span>lula fire line</span><span>narvik night set</span><span>pomegranate medovik</span><span>charcoal line</span><span>midday lunch set</span><span>ukrainian comfort</span><span>azerbaijani fire</span><span>borscht reserve</span><span>lula fire line</span><span>narvik night set</span><span>pomegranate medovik</span></div></div></div></section>
<section class="gm-section gm-sectionLight" id="menu-wall"><div class="gm-wrap"><span class="gm-eyebrow gm-reveal">Menu wall</span><h2 class="gm-heading gm-reveal">A menu with campaigns, categories and scene changes.</h2><p class="gm-body gm-reveal">The reels showed that premium design often comes from staging and sequencing, not from more widgets. So this menu is arranged like a branded wall: category tabs, a large statement panel, and food cards that read like editorial entries instead of marketplace tiles.</p><div class="gm-menuShell gm-reveal"><div class="gm-tabBar">@foreach($menuGroups as $index => $group)<button class="gm-tab {{ $index === 0 ? 'is-active' : '' }}" type="button" data-menu-tab="{{ $group['id'] }}">{{ $group['label'] }}</button>@endforeach</div>@foreach($menuGroups as $index => $group)<div class="gm-menuPanel {{ $index !== 0 ? 'gm-hidden' : '' }}" data-menu-panel="{{ $group['id'] }}"><div class="gm-menuStage"><article class="gm-menuInfo"><span class="gm-kicker" style="padding:8px 13px;font-size:10px">{{ $group['label'] }} selection</span><h3>{{ $group['headline'] }}</h3><p>{{ $group['copy'] }}</p></article><div class="gm-menuCards">@foreach($group['items'] as $item)<article class="gm-menuCard"><div class="gm-menuCardTop"><h4>{{ $item['name'] }}</h4><span class="gm-price">{{ number_format($item['price'],0) }} NOK</span></div><p>{{ $item['note'] }}</p></article>@endforeach</div></div></div>@endforeach</div></div></section>
<section class="gm-section" id="promos" style="padding-top:0"><div class="gm-wrap"><span class="gm-eyebrow gm-reveal" style="color:rgba(245,236,221,.56)">Advertising blocks</span><h2 class="gm-heading gm-reveal">Campaigns that look like restaurant ads, not admin banners.</h2><p class="gm-body gm-reveal" style="color:var(--gm-muted)">You asked for menu, advertising and stronger thematic blocks. These promos are designed as house campaigns: lunch, evening grill and dessert close, each with its own mood and color temperature.</p><div class="gm-promoGrid">@foreach($promoPanels as $panel)<article class="gm-promo gm-reveal" data-tone="{{ $panel['tone'] }}"><small>{{ $panel['eyebrow'] }}</small><h3>{{ $panel['title'] }}</h3><p>{{ $panel['copy'] }}</p></article>@endforeach</div></div></section>
<section class="gm-section gm-sectionLight" id="experience" style="padding-top:0"><div class="gm-wrap"><span class="gm-eyebrow gm-reveal">Experience logic</span><h2 class="gm-heading gm-reveal">Quality comes from direction, not decoration.</h2><p class="gm-body gm-reveal">Across the reference videos, the most convincing designs used fewer objects with more intent. This version follows that principle: one strong hero, one menu wall, one promo grid, one operations block. The result is bolder, cleaner and more ownable for GLF MaT.</p><div class="gm-service">@foreach($serviceNotes as $note)<article class="gm-note gm-reveal"><strong>{{ $note['index'] }}</strong><h3>{{ $note['title'] }}</h3><p>{{ $note['text'] }}</p></article>@endforeach</div></div></section>
<section class="gm-section gm-sectionLight" id="roster" style="padding-top:0"><div class="gm-wrap"><div class="gm-rosterHead"><div><span class="gm-eyebrow gm-reveal">Live kitchens</span><h2 class="gm-heading gm-reveal">Operational data still stays visible.</h2></div><p class="gm-body gm-reveal">The page is art-directed, but it still needs to work as part of the product. These cards stay connected to the real active kitchens and delivery metadata already present on the server.</p></div><div class="gm-roster">@forelse($restaurantCards as $restaurant)<article class="gm-rosterCard gm-reveal"><div class="gm-rosterCardTop"><div><h3>{{ $restaurant['name'] }}</h3><p style="margin:10px 0 0">{{ $restaurant['cuisine'] }}</p></div><span class="gm-badge">{{ $restaurant['delivery'] }} min</span></div><div class="gm-rosterMeta"><div><strong>Address:</strong> {{ $restaurant['address'] ?: 'Narvik' }}</div><div><strong>Delivery fee:</strong> {{ number_format($restaurant['fee'],0) }} NOK</div><div><strong>Minimum:</strong> {{ number_format($restaurant['minimum'],0) }} NOK</div></div><a href="{{ route('public.restaurants.show', $restaurant['slug']) }}">Open restaurant profile</a></article>@empty<article class="gm-rosterCard gm-reveal" style="grid-column:1/-1"><h3>Kitchen roster is being prepared.</h3><p>The design is ready, but the current dataset returned no active food-delivery kitchens.</p></article>@endforelse</div><div class="gm-close gm-reveal"><div class="gm-closeGrid"><div><h2>GLF MaT now has its own design language.</h2><p>No embedded reference videos, no copied layouts, and no generic food grid. The page now uses the reels only as a quality benchmark and turns that into its own restaurant-campaign system built specifically for Ukrainian and Azerbaijani cuisine.</p><div class="gm-actions" style="margin-top:24px"><a class="gm-btn" href="{{ route('public.restaurants.index') }}">Browse restaurants</a><a class="gm-btnGhost" href="{{ route('food') }}">Reload food page</a></div></div><aside class="gm-closingBadge"><img src="{{ $logoUrl }}" alt="GLF MaT logo badge"><strong>Brand-first close</strong><span style="color:rgba(33,24,19,.68);line-height:1.6">The user leaves the route remembering the restaurant mark, the menu wall and the fire/comfort contrast.</span></aside></div></div></div></section>
<script>(function(){var tabs=[].slice.call(document.querySelectorAll('[data-menu-tab]')),panels=[].slice.call(document.querySelectorAll('[data-menu-panel]')),reveals=[].slice.call(document.querySelectorAll('.gm-reveal'));function show(id){tabs.forEach(function(tab){tab.classList.toggle('is-active',tab.getAttribute('data-menu-tab')===id)});panels.forEach(function(panel){panel.classList.toggle('gm-hidden',panel.getAttribute('data-menu-panel')!==id)})}tabs.forEach(function(tab){tab.addEventListener('click',function(){show(tab.getAttribute('data-menu-tab'))})});if('IntersectionObserver'in window){var observer=new IntersectionObserver(function(entries){entries.forEach(function(entry){if(!entry.isIntersecting)return;entry.target.classList.add('is-visible');observer.unobserve(entry.target)})},{threshold:.14,rootMargin:'0px 0px -10% 0px'});reveals.forEach(function(node,index){if(index<4)node.classList.add('is-visible');observer.observe(node)})}else{reveals.forEach(function(node){node.classList.add('is-visible')})}show('ukrainian')})();</script>
</div>
@endsection
